questionRound.0.question.9.answer: I always looked at the box farthest to the right. That box will always have a row that guarantees a higher payoff than the other row. Then  I would predict what the other people would choose and move from box to box until I got to my own. Most of the time  I could not pick the row with the highest payoff because the pattern would not give me the highest payoff.

There was always one color with an easy choice because one entire row's numbers were higher than the other row's numbers. Then I went back color by color from there making the best choices based on what the given original choice was. Down the line  the best choice was not always the highest of the four numbers  but I tried to make the best decision out of the two numbers that I predicted the other players would choose.
There was always one choice that was best for a particular player and then in turn best for the next.

If you were assigned to the color on the very right  it was pretty simple: you choose the outcome with the higher result.  | If you were assigned to the colors otherwise  you would look at the results on the table on the right of your selected color and figure out which would give you the best outcome.

Went in order from the right to the left  viewing the payoffs for each quadrant  and making informed guesses about what each player would make based on what the payoffs were. In each game  the player on the far right always had an obvious decision which made it very simple to predict what everyone else would do. If it wasn't like that  it would have been a lot harder.
I start from the right table to see what color the person will choose works best for him/her. Then move left to see what works for everyone.
I always looked at the last box first and predicted what would be chosen from it and then worked backwards from there.
I based my answer on what I thought others would choose. I would try to find a player who would definitely choose a certain option and go off of that.

I went through the rest of the colors and assumed that they would choose a larger number to earn more money and based on their possible choices I made my choice so that I wouldn't lose as much money instead of just choosing the one with the largest number.

I started from the left side  because that matrix always had one option where the payoff would benefit no matter which option the other person chose (there was an option that clearly gave the most payoff). I would assume that the person would choose the option with the most payoff  and in the matrix on the immediate left  would choose the option that yields the most payoff given that the previous person chose their  most profitable option. I continued this process until I got to the matrix that gave my payoff. I was choosing options that gave me the most payoff  and I assumed that other players would do the same because I assumed we all acted upon self-interest.

After a few rounds of playing  I noticed that the colour on the far right is often an easy choice--a choice's two numbers is often bigger than the two numbers of the other choice  as in that a choice's smallest number is bigger than the other number's biggest number. Hence  it is an "easy choice" and if I end up on the far right  I simply choose the choice with the bigger numbers. If I am more to the left  I presume that everyone has noticed that the colour on the far right is an easy choice and will make the choice based on that--and I follow the good outcome "along the line" and get my choice based on the choice of the colour on the direct right of my colour.

In the four game sessions  there was usually one color that had the opportunity of gaining the most money with one option. From there I assumed others would see that  and after that I went directly to the color that would be directly affected by the first color's option. I assumed the second color would choose the best option for itself and then from there I went to the next color and assumed it would choose the best option for itself  also assuming that this third color would assume what I assumed the second color would choose. |  | In the three game sessions  I hoped the other colors would choose the option that would make sense for every color. In hopes that they feared the lower numbers I assumed they would choose the option that would benefit themselves  in collaboration with what would be the most reasonable option for the other colors assuming the same things.
